    <TD><B>N=B0&nbsp;33-1996:&nbsp;&nbsp;Ariane 501 - Presentation of =
Inquiry=20
      Board report</B><BR>&nbsp;<BR>&nbsp;<BR><B>23 July 1996</B><BR>On =
4 June=20
      1996 the maiden flight of the Ariane 5 launcher ended in a =
failure. Only=20
      about 40 seconds after initiation of the flight sequence, at an =
altitude=20
      of about 3700 m, the launcher veered off its flight path, broke up =
and=20
      exploded.<BR>&nbsp;<BR>Mr Jean-Marie Luton, ESA Director General, =
and Mr=20
      Alain Bensoussan, CNES Chairman, immediately set up an independent =
Inquiry=20
      Board (see ESA-CNES Press Release of 10 June 1996), which has now=20
      submitted its report.
      <P>The report begins by presenting the causes of the failure, =
analysis of=20
      the flight data having indicated:
      <P>
      <UL>
        <LI>nominal behaviour of the launcher up to H0 + 36 seconds;=20
        <LI>simultaneous failure of the two inertial reference systems;=20
        <LI>swivelling into the extreme position of the nozzles of the =
two solid=20
        boosters and, slightly later, of the Vulcain engine, causing the =

        launcher to veer abruptly;=20
        <LI>self-destruction of the launcher correctly triggered by =
rupture of=20
        the electrical links between the solid boosters and the core =
stage.=20
      </LI></UL>
      <P>A chain of events, their inter-relations and causes have been=20
      established, starting with the destruction of the launcher and =
tracing=20
      back in time towards the primary cause. These provide the =
technical=20
      explanations for the failure of the 501 flight, which lay in the =
flight=20
      control and guidance system. A detailed account is given in the =
report,=20
      which concludes:
      <P><I>" The failure of Ariane 501 was caused by the complete loss =
of=20
      guidance and attitude information 37 seconds after start of the =
main=20
      engine ignition sequence (30 seconds after lift-off). This loss of =

      information was due to specification and design errors in the =
software of=20
      the inertial reference system. The extensive reviews and tests =
carried out=20
      during the Ariane 5 development programme did not include adequate =

      analysis and testing of the inertial reference system or of the =
complete=20
      flight control system, which could have detected the potential=20
      failure."</I>
      <P>Despite the series of tests and reviews carried out under the=20
      programme, in the course of which thousands of corrections were =
made,=20
      shortcomings in the system approach concerning the software =
resulted in=20
      failure to detect the fault. It is stressed that alignement =
function of=20
      the inertial reference system, which served a purpose only before =
lift-off=20
      (but remained operative afterwards), was not taken into account in =
the=20
      simulations and that the equipment and system tests were not =
sufficiently=20
      representative.
      <P>Without implicating the system architecture, the report makes a =
series=20
      of recommendations for ensuring that the launcher's software =
operates=20
      correctly. The Ariane 5 programme will be taking action in line =
with all=20
      these recommendations, as follows:
      <P>
      <UL>
        <LI>correction of the problem in the SRI (inertial reference =
system)=20
        that led to the accident;=20
        <LI>reexamination of all software embedded in equipment;=20
        <LI>improvement of the representativeness (vis-a-vis the =
launcher) of=20
        the qualification testing environment;=20
        <LI>introduction of overlaps and deliberate redundancy between=20
        successive tests:<BR>
        <DD>-at equipment level, <BR>
        <DD>-at stage level, <BR>
        <DD>-at system level; <BR></DD>
        <LI>improvement and systematisation of the two-way flow of =
information:=20
        <DD>-up from equipment to system: nominal and failure-mode =
behaviour;=20
        <BR>
        <DD>-down from system to equipment: use of equipment items in=20
        flight.</DD></LI></UL>
      <P>More specifically, the following corrective measures will be =
applied:
      <UL>
        <LI>to the inertial reference system: <BR>
        <DD>-switch-off or inhibition of the alignment function after =
liftoff,=20
        <BR>
        <DD>-analysis/modification of processing, particularly on =
detection of a=20
        fault (no processor shutdown), <BR>
        <DD>-testing to check the coverage of the SRI flight domain; =
<BR></DD>
        <LI>to the system qualification environment:=20
        <DD>-general improvement of representativeness through =
systematic use of=20
        real equipment and components wherever possible, <BR>
        <DD>-simulation of real trajectories on SRI electronics. =
<BR></DD>
        <LI>In addition, the following general measures will be taken: =
<BR>
        <DD>-critical reappraisal of all software (flight program and =
embedded=20
        software), <BR>
        <DD>-review of mechanisms for managing double failures, <BR>
        <DD>-improvement of facilities for acquisition and retrieval of=20
        telemetry data, <BR>
        <DD>-improvement of overall coordination relating to software.=20
      </DD></LI></UL>The ESA Director General and CNES Chairman will be =
making a=20
      joint presentation of the plan of action put into effect and its=20
      programmatic consequences at a press conference in September.=20
      <P><IMG src=3D"http://ravel.esrin.esa.it/images/pdflogo.gif"=20
      align=3Dtop>&nbsp;<A=20
      href=3D"http://ravel.esrin.esa.it/docs/esa-x-1819eng.pdf">Ariane 5 =
flight=20
      105 Inquiry Board report =BB</A><BR>&nbsp;<BR></P></TD></TR>
